Basic Goal: Is recall systematically distorted based on statistical regularities? How are these distortions characterized in terms of unbiased, biased, and guess distributions?

Below is a summary of the behavioral experiment that was run (Exp 1), followed by current modeling approaches. Then I present a replication of the experiment (with small tweak) that I ran the first few weeks of the semester (Exp 2). There are some comments throughout and potential next steps at the end.

Exp 1¶

Design¶

20 participants were collected (4 excluded due to <80% performance at repeat detection task)

Study Phase¶

  • 336 objects presented sequentially, with color sampling from a biased color wheel partitioned into 4 quadrants. One quadrant ("rich quadrant") is preferentially sampled so that 50% of objects are in this color region. Quadrants are randomly selected for every subject, and sampling follows a uniform distribution for each quadrant.

  • An additional 30 objects are presented at random times throughout study phase, in which these objects are presented twice in a row. The task is to press the spacebar whenever an object immediately repeats. These repeated objects are not presented in the test phase. Therefore the total trial count for the study phase was 336 + (30*2) = 396.

Test Phase¶

  • Continuous color report

Non-modelling Behavioral Results¶

Here I have characterized the color responses for each subject according to whether their response was closer/towards to the rich quadrant or farther/away from the rich quadrant, compared to the original color. (Note that some trials are discarded because they either answered the color exactly correct, exactly 180 degrees away from the correct color, or they clicked without moving the mouse which invalidated the trial.)

Some problems with Exp 1:

  • Colors were not isoluminant across objects, due to objects having different shading.
  • Did not record the original trial that each tested object was originally displayed at, which could have been useful for follow-up analyses.
  • Did not do explicit continuous color response judgment at the end to gauge whether they realized the preferential color sampling. Instead did a 2AFC between 24 pairs of colors equidistant around the color wheel and a post-survey in which they were asked if they noticed colors were more likely to be of a certain color.

Post-survey: Do you think you selected certain colors more often than others, and if so what color?

Everyone said that they did think so, and approximately 1/3 of them correctly stated the color? Although this question I think could have been phrased much better, and some people didn't even state a color other than typing "yes".

Implicit memory test: 24 trials 15 degree mirrored color patch comparisons, asked which color appeared more frequently across objects

Only 2 people chose the color closer to the rich quadrant on over 60% of trials.

Comments¶

While all the above individual subjects converged, some of them messed up really bad. Huge standard deviations or a near zero guess distribution. I can of course limit the standard deviation max, but this is a concern. We need to consider what criteria to use to eliminate subjects, as some show pretty much no target distribution which of course the model will have trouble with.

Exp 2¶

Design¶

  • 20 participants were again collected (nobody was excluded due to repeat detection task)

  • 324 objects presented, this time using objects with modified color so all objects truly were sampled from the same isoluminant color wheel:

  • Posterized stimuli (basically divide image into only 3 colors):

  • Did record the study trial for object presentation to be compared with individual test trial, and did do explicit continuous color report (but not implicit color report) as well as the post-survey.

It seems like a number of individual fits don't make sense... I'm looking at some graphs and thinking the std for the biased distribution here is way too high, or the biased mean was placed completely off the mark.

  • Mean guessing distribution across individuals: 53.1%
  • Mean biased distribution across individuals: 30.8%
  • This means target distribution was the remainder, or approximately 16.1% of responses
  • Mean stdev of target distribution across individuals: 25.7
  • Mean stdev of biased distribution across individuals: 85.5

Comments, Future Directions¶

First, we need to figure out some exclusion criteria. I initially thought it could be something simple like, exclude if it doesn't fit a standard mixture model, but apparently even extremely messy data can still converge on these models. So perhaps exclude based on some other criteria?

The data for Expt. 2 looks much more messy than Expt 1. This may be because of the objects looking somewhat degraded due to the posterization, or the fact that all objects now share the exact same color wheel makes remembering more difficult. I may need to reduce the number of objects from 300-something to 200-something to find more reliable behavioral performance using posterized objects. However, this may lead to tradeoff where less trials makes modelling individuals more difficult. Else, I may want to replicate Expt. 1 simply to correct for the problems I outlined above (aside from the posterization).

I also now coded up a confidence report that may be used (specifying a range of values the subject believes the correct color may lie). This may be helpful in figuring out how bias relates to confidence in responses.

Unfortunately, slots for this week are not getting filled up (likely because midterms and it being the Spring?). I do have, however, have an mTurk version of the experiment nearly all ready to go if we want to collect data more quickly (you can see what it currently looks like here: https://paulscotti.github.io/mturk/Cont_LTM_101_3).
